{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501311"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1744"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1744"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.06,0.18,0.09,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1744"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107199"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1744"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1744"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89652"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16539"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44709"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107199"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department complaining of central chest pain starting about 20 minutes ago. He feels \u0022like his heart is beating out of his chest\u0022. His wife says that he has diabetes and \u0022kidney failure\u0022, but cannot give any more details.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he is pale and sweaty, with a blood pressure of 110/60 mmHg, pulse 98/min and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. A 12-lead ECG is immediately obtained (image), and blood tests are taken to check for cardiac biomarkers and electrolyte levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperkalaemia","Ventricular fibrillation","Ventricular tachycardia","Torsades de Pointes","Acute pericarditis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chest pain and palpitations in the context of known renal failure, which places him at high risk for electrolyte abnormalities. The ECG shows characteristic changes of severe hyperkalaemia including peaked T waves, P wave flattening, PR prolongation, and QRS widening with abnormal morphology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as a serum concentration \u0026gt;5.5 mEq/L in adults (normal range = 3.5-5.5 mEq/L). As the level rises, the risk of arrhythmias including ventricular fibrillation and asystole increases due to altered cardiac membrane excitability. Progressive hyperkalaemia is associated with characteristic ECG changes, which are observed on this patient\u0027s ECG: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeaked T waves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EP wave flattening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPR prolongation (often hidden due to the widened QRS complex).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EQRS widening with abnormal morphology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese findings usually correlate with a very high potassium level. Conduction blocks and bradyarrhythmias are other common features of hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important shockable cardiac arrest rhythm and can be fatal unless advanced life support is initiated. Although the most common presentation for VF is sudden collapse, patients may also show signs such as chest pain, dyspnoea, nausea and vomiting. ECG findings include no identifiable P waves, QRS complexes or T waves, irregular deflections of varying amplitude, rate of 150-500 per minute and decreasing amplitude with duration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad complex tachycardia that originates at the ventricles and can impair cardiac output with consequent hypotension and possible acute cardiac failure. On an ECG, a ventricular tachycardia will show a rapid heart rate (above 100bpm), broad QRS complexes (above 160ms), AV dissociation (the P wave and QRS complexes occur at different rates), and right axis deviation (QRS is positive in lead aVR and negative in leads I and aVF). The ECG shown above does not meet the criteria to be considered a ventricular tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETorsades de Pointes\u003C/strong\u003E is a specific form of polymorphic ventricular tachycardia (PVT). On ECG the characteristic finding is a twisting of the QRS complexes around an isoelectric line. To be diagnosed, a patient must have evidence of both PVT (which has multiple ventricular foci with QRS complexes varying in amplitude, axis and duration) and QT prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E ECG changes include widespread ST elevation and PR depression in limb leads (leads I, II, III, aVL, and aVF) as well as in precordial leads V2-6. Reciprocal ST depression and PR elevation in lead aVR and V1 may also be seen. Sinus tachycardia is also a common ECG characteristic of acute pericarditis due to pericardial effusion. These ECG changes can not be seen in the ECG shown above.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyperkalaemia is associated with a characteristic progression of ECG changes.","Patients with renal failure are at high risk of developing life-threatening hyperkalaemia.","ECG changes in hyperkalaemia include peaked T waves, P wave flattening, PR prolongation, and QRS widening."],"references":["Morris F, Brady WJ. ABC of clinical electrocardiography: Acute myocardial infarction-Part I. BMJ. 2002;324:831-4. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1122768/","Littmann L, Gibbs MA. Electrocardiographic manifestations of severe hyperkalemia. J Electrocardiol. 2018; 51:814-17. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30177318/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89652"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1744"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"2172"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"2172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/2172"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/14ce3687-beb5-4acd-b01d-119440af6641.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/14ce3687-beb5-4acd-b01d-119440af6641.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":386}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89652"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-26T01:32:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T01:32:47+09:30"},"relatio